 upon the literary, religious, social and political life of men, women and children throughout Europe and beyond continues to excite lively debate among historians, as the ten papers presented in this volume confirm. They deal with theresponse of urban communities in England, France and Italy to matters of public health, governance and welfare, as well as addressing the reactions of the medical profession to successive outbreaks of disease, and of individuals to the omnipresence of death, while two, very different, essays examine the important, if sometimes controversial, contribution now being made by microbiologists to our understanding of the Black Death. Contributors: J.L. Bolton, Elma Brenner, Samuel Cohn, John Henderson, Neil Murphy, Elizabeth Rutledge, Samantha Sagui, Karen Smyth, Jane Stevens Crawshaw, Sheila Sweetinburgh.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPlaguezEuropexHistory. 0aPlaguezGreat BritainxHistory. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aHistory of Science & Medicine. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAge of Plague.  aBlack Death.  aDeath.  aEpidemics.  aEurope.  aGovernance.  aMedical Profession.  aMicrobiologists.  aPathogens.  aPublic Health.  aSociety.  aThe Fifteenth Century XII.  aWelfare.1 aBolton, J.L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBolton, Jim L, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrenner, Elma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Linda, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCohn, Samuel K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrawshaw, Jane Stevens, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel